The history of computer science. It’s a long, convoluted story, isn’t it? Like trying to trace the lineage of a particularly stubborn stain. Most of it happened long before the actual discipline decided to show its face, masquerading as mere [mathematics](/Mathematics) or [physics](/Physics). But beneath the surface, the seeds were sown. Developments from centuries past, mere whispers of what was to come, eventually coalesced into the field we now call computer science. It's a progression, really, from clunky mechanical contraptions and abstract [mathematical](/Mathematics) theories to the sleek, almost sentient machines of today. This journey wasn't just about building better gadgets; it birthed a major [academic discipline](/Academic_discipline), fueled technological leaps across the [Western world](/Western_world), and laid the groundwork for the vast, interconnected global trade and culture we navigate now. &#91;1&#93; &#91;2&#93;

### Prehistory

Before we had silicon chips and endless lines of code, there was the [abacus](/Abacus). Developed around 2700–2300 BCE in [Sumer](/Sumer), it was the earliest known tool for computation. Imagine it: columns etched into sand, pebbles marking the passage of numbers in their [sexagesimal](/Sexagesimal) system. &#91;3&#93; &#91;4&#93; It’s a primitive ancestor, certainly, but its lineage persists; variations of the abacus are still in use today, like the elegant [Chinese abacus](/Chinese_abacus). &#91;5&#93;

Fast forward to the 5th century BC in [ancient India](/History_of_India). A grammarian named [Pāṇini](/P%C4%81%E1%B9%87ini) crafted the [grammar](/Grammar) of [Sanskrit](/Sanskrit) into 3959 rules, a system so precise and technical it foreshadowed computational logic. He employed metarules, [transformations](/Transformational_grammar), and [recursions](/Recursion) – concepts that would echo much later in the digital realm. &#91;6&#93;

Then there's the [Antikythera mechanism](/Antikythera_mechanism), a relic from around 100 BC. Discovered in 1901 off the coast of Greece, this intricate device is believed to be an early mechanical analog computer, designed to chart the heavens. &#91;7&#93; It's a testament to ingenuity, a mechanical mind lost to time until its rediscovery.

A millennium later, the [medieval Islamic world](/Islamic_Golden_Age) saw a resurgence of such complex analog devices. Muslim astronomers, like [Abū Rayhān al-Bīrūnī](/Ab%C5%AB_Rayh%C4%81n_al-B%C4%ABr%C5%ABn%C4%AB), developed geared [astrolabes](/Astrolabe), and [Jabir ibn Aflah](/Jabir_ibn_Aflah) created the [torquetum](/Torquetum). &#91;8&#93; &#91;9&#93; And let's not forget the strides in [cryptography](/Cryptography). As [Simon Singh](/Simon_Singh) notes, [Muslim mathematicians](/Islamic_mathematics) like [Alkindus](/Al-Kindi) pioneered [cryptanalysis](/Cryptanalysis) and [frequency analysis](/Frequency_analysis). &#91;10&#93; &#91;11&#93; Even programmable machines emerged from this era, with the [Banū Mūsā](/Ban%C5%AB_M%C5%ABs%C4%81) brothers creating an automatic [flute](/Flute) player – a rather elegant precursor to automation. &#91;12&#93;

Europe, too, caught up with its own mechanical marvels, with intricate [astronomical clocks](/Astronomical_clock) appearing in the 14th century. &#91;13&#93;

The 17th century brought [John Napier](/John_Napier) and his groundbreaking discovery of [logarithms](/Logarithm) for calculation. &#91;14&#93; This spurred a wave of innovation. [Wilhelm Schickard](/Wilhelm_Schickard) designed a calculating machine for [Johannes Kepler](/Johannes_Kepler) in 1623, though a fire in 1624 tragically destroyed the prototype. &#91;15&#93; Around 1640, [Blaise Pascal](/Blaise_Pascal), a luminary of French mathematics, built an adding device, drawing inspiration from the ancient Greek mathematician [Hero of Alexandria](/Hero_of_Alexandria). &#91;16&#93; Then came [Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz](/Gottfried_Wilhelm_Leibniz) and his [Stepped Reckoner](/Stepped_Reckoner), completed in 1694. &#91;17&#93;

But the true blueprint for the modern computer arrived in 1837 with [Charles Babbage](/Charles_Babbage) and his [Analytical Engine](/Analytical_Engine). This wasn't just a calculator; it possessed expandable memory, an arithmetic unit, and the capacity for logic processing, capable of interpreting a [programming language](/Programming_language) with loops and conditional branching. It was never built, a ghost of a machine, but its design was so advanced it's considered [Turing equivalent](/Turing_complete). Imagine: less than a [kilobyte](/Kilobyte) of memory and a [clock speed](/Clock_rate) under 10 [Hertz](/Hertz). &#91;18&#93; Of course, all this required advancements in [electronics](/Electronics) theory and pure mathematics, which were still in their nascent stages.

### Binary Logic

[Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz](/Gottfried_Wilhelm_Leibniz) – a name that surfaces again and again. In 1702, he laid the groundwork for [logic](/Logic) as a formal, mathematical discipline with his exploration of the [binary number](/Binary_number) system. He’s practically the patron saint of computer science, simplifying binary and articulating fundamental logical properties. &#91;19&#93; &#91;20&#93; He even anticipated concepts like [Lagrangian interpolation](/Lagrange_polynomial) and [algorithmic information theory](/Algorithmic_information_theory), and his [calculus ratiocinator](/Calculus_ratiocinator) hinted at the [universal Turing machine](/Universal_Turing_machine). In 1961, [Norbert Wiener](/Norbert_Wiener) even declared Leibniz the patron saint of [cybernetics](/Cybernetics), noting that a computing machine is essentially a mechanization of Leibniz's *Calculus Ratiocinator*. &#91;21&#93; &#91;22&#93;

However, it took over a century for [George Boole](/George_Boole) to publish his [Boolean algebra](/Boolean_algebra_(logic)) in 1854, providing the mathematical framework for computational processes. &#91;23&#93;

Meanwhile, the [Industrial Revolution](/Industrial_Revolution) was busy mechanizing everything, including [weaving](/Weaving). [Joseph Marie Jacquard](/Joseph_Marie_Jacquard)'s loom, controlled by [punched cards](/Punched_cards) in 1801, demonstrated how binary patterns could drive machines. A hole meant a one, no hole meant a zero. While no computer, it was a tangible example of binary control. &#91;23&#93;

### Emergence of a Discipline

[Charles Babbage](/Charles_Babbage) – the visionary. From the 1810s, he dreamt of mechanical computation. He designed calculators, then the ambitious "Analytical Engine" – a machine that could use punched cards for operations, store numbers, and execute instructions sequentially. This was the first true representation of a modern computer. &#91;24&#93;

And then there's [Ada Lovelace](/Ada_Lovelace). A mathematical prodigy, she worked with Babbage and is credited as the pioneer of computer programming. She designed the first algorithm, capable of computing [Bernoulli numbers](/Bernoulli_numbers) – though arguably, Babbage himself was the first to design algorithms for his Difference Engine. &#91;25&#93; &#91;26&#93; Lovelace also predicted that computers wouldn't just crunch numbers; they'd manipulate symbols, any kind of data. Her work, though unrealized in her lifetime, laid crucial conceptual groundwork. &#91;27&#93; &#91;28&#93;

#### Early Post-Analytical Engine Designs

Others followed Babbage's conceptual trail. [Percy Ludgate], unaware of Babbage's work, independently designed a programmable mechanical computer, detailed in a 1909 publication. &#91;29&#93; &#91;30&#93;

[Leonardo Torres Quevedo](/Leonardo_Torres_Quevedo) and [Vannevar Bush](/Vannevar_Bush) also contributed. Torres, in his 1914 *Essays on Automatics*, proposed an electromechanical machine controlled by a [read-only](/Read-only_memory) program and introduced the concept of [floating-point arithmetic](/Floating-point_arithmetic). &#91;31&#93; &#91;32&#93; &#91;33&#93; By 1920, he'd presented an [Electromechanical Arithmometer](/Leonardo_Torres_y_Quevedo) that could be remotely controlled via typewriter. &#91;34&#93; Bush, in his 1936 paper *Instrumental Analysis*, explored using IBM punch card machines for Babbage's designs and began the Rapid Arithmetical Machine project. &#91;35&#93;

#### Charles Sanders Peirce and Electrical Switching Circuits

[Charles Sanders Peirce](/Charles_Sanders_Peirce), a philosopher and logician, described in an 1886 letter how logical operations could be performed by [electrical switching circuits](/Switching_circuit_theory). &#91;36&#93; He even showed, in unpublished manuscripts from 1880-81, that [NOR gates alone](/NOR_logic) (or [NAND gates alone](/NAND_logic)) could perform all logical operations. &#91;37&#93; This concept of universal gates was later published by [Henry M. Sheffer](/Henry_M._Sheffer) and [Walther Bothe](/Walther_Bothe) developed the first modern electronic AND gate in 1924. &#91;38&#93; &#91;39&#93;

By the 1930s, electrical engineers were building circuits for computation, but it was [Claude Shannon](/Claude_Shannon)'s 1937 master's thesis that truly formalized this. He demonstrated how [Boole's](/George_Boole) [Boolean algebra](/Boolean_algebra) could be applied to electromechanical relays, laying the foundation for digital circuit design. &#91;40&#93; &#91;41&#93; &#91;42&#93; &#91;43&#93;

#### Alan Turing and the Turing Machine

Before the 1920s, "computers" were human clerks, diligently performing calculations, often under the guidance of physicists. &#91;45&#93; &#91;46&#93; &#91;47&#93; &#91;48&#93; They crunched numbers for everything from astronomical tables to ballistic calculations. &#91;49&#93;

After the 1920s, the term "computing machine" emerged, referring to any device that could automate these human computations according to defined methods, as outlined in the [Church-Turing thesis](/Church-Turing_thesis). Analog machines represented continuous values, while digital machines handled discrete digits, initially using relays before faster memory devices arrived. The term "computer" gradually shifted to exclusively mean electronic digital machines after the late 1940s. These machines could perform any task that could be described as "purely mechanical," a concept formalized by [Alan Turing](/Alan_Turing)'s theoretical [Turing Machine](/Turing_Machine). &#91;52&#93;

The theoretical underpinnings of modern computer science were also being shaped by [Kurt Gödel](/Kurt_G%C3%B6del) and his 1931 [incompleteness theorem](/G%C3%B6del%27s_incompleteness_theorems), which revealed the inherent limits of formal systems. &#91;50&#93;

In 1936, Alan Turing and [Alonzo Church](/Alonzo_Church) independently formalized the concept of an [algorithm](/Algorithm) and its computational limits, leading to the [Church–Turing thesis](/Church%E2%80%93Turing_thesis). &#91;51&#93; Turing's work on the [Turing machines](/Turing_machine), particularly the [Universal Turing machine](/Universal_Turing_machine), introduced the fundamental concept of the modern computer and the [stored program](/Stored_program) idea. &#91;52&#93; These abstract machines helped define what is [Turing computable](/Turing_computable). &#91;53&#93;

Physicist [Stanley Frankel](/Stanley_Frankel) recounted [John von Neumann](/John_von_Neumann)'s profound respect for Turing's 1936 paper, stating that von Neumann himself emphasized that the fundamental conception was "owing to Turing." &#91;52&#93;

#### Kathleen Booth and the First Assembly Language

[Kathleen Booth]() developed the first [assembly language](/Assembly_language) and designed the assembler and autocode for the Automatic Relay Calculator (ARC) at [Birkbeck College, University of London](/Birkbeck,_University_of_London). She was instrumental in designing three machines: the ARC, the SEC, and the [APE(X)C](/APEXC). &#91;54&#93;

### Early Computer Hardware

The world's first electronic digital computer, the [Atanasoff–Berry computer](/Atanasoff%E2%80%93Berry_computer), was built at Iowa State between 1939 and 1942 by [John V. Atanasoff](/John_Vincent_Atanasoff) and [Clifford Berry](/Clifford_Berry).

In 1941, [Konrad Zuse](/Konrad_Zuse) unveiled the [Z3](/Z3_(computer)], the world's first functional program-controlled computer, later proven to be [Turing-complete](/Turing_completeness) in principle. &#91;57&#93; &#91;58&#93; Zuse also developed the S2, an early [process control](/Process_control) computer, and founded one of the first computer businesses, producing the [Z4](/Z4_(computer)), the first commercial computer. In 1946, he designed [Plankalkül](/Plankalk%C3%BCl), the first [high-level programming language](/High-level_programming_language). &#91;59&#93;

The [Manchester Baby](/Manchester_Baby), completed in 1948, was the world's first electronic digital computer to store programs in its memory, a crucial step towards modern computing. &#91;52&#93; Turing's work was a significant influence on its development. &#91;52&#93;

Britain's [National Physical Laboratory](/National_Physical_Laboratory,_UK) completed the [Pilot ACE](/Pilot_ACE) in 1950, a small programmable computer based on Turing's designs. It operated at 1 MHz, making it the fastest computer of its time. &#91;52&#93; &#91;60&#93; Turing's ambitious ACE design incorporated concepts similar to today's [RISC](/RISC) architectures. &#91;52&#93;

The first [operating system](/Operating_system), [GM-NAA I/O](/GM-NAA_I/O), designed for [batch processing](/Batch_processing) to reduce operator intervention, was developed in the late 1950s by [General Motors](/General_Motors) and [North American Aviation](/North_American_Aviation) for the [IBM 701](/IBM_701).

An experiment in 1969 by teams at UCLA and Stanford attempted to link two computers, a foundational step towards the [Internet](/History_of_the_Internet), despite an initial system crash.

The first actual computer "bug" was a real moth, found trapped in the relays of the Harvard Mark II. &#91;61&#93; While [Grace Hopper](/Grace_Hopper) is often credited with coining the term, the actual log entry dates to September 9, 1947. &#91;61&#93;

#### Shannon and Information Theory

[Claude Shannon](/Claude_Shannon), a true visionary, founded the field of [information theory](/Information_theory) with his 1948 paper, *[A Mathematical Theory of Communication](/A_Mathematical_Theory_of_Communication)*. He applied [probability theory](/Probability_theory) to the challenge of efficient information transmission, a work that underpins [data compression](/Data_compression) and [cryptography](/Cryptography). &#91;62&#93;

#### Wiener and Cybernetics

[Norbert Wiener](/Norbert_Wiener), drawing from his work on anti-aircraft systems, coined the term [cybernetics](/Cybernetics) from the Greek word for "steersman." His 1948 book *Cybernetics* significantly influenced the nascent field of [artificial intelligence](/Artificial_intelligence). He also explored the parallels between [computation](/Computation), machinery, [memory](/Computer_memory), and the human brain. &#91;63&#93;

#### John von Neumann and the Von Neumann Architecture

In 1946, [John von Neumann](/John_von_Neumann) introduced a model for computer architecture that would become known as the [Von Neumann architecture](/Von_Neumann_architecture). &#91; [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed) &#93; This design, which allowed instructions and data to share memory, became the standard for subsequent computer designs. It comprises the arithmetic logic unit (ALU), memory, and the instruction processing unit (IPU). &#91;64&#93;

Von Neumann's architecture, often debated regarding its RISC classification, &#91; [dubious](/Wikipedia:Accuracy_dispute)&#32;&#8211; [discuss](/Talk:History_of_computer_science) &#93; uses a limited instruction set. It features a main memory and an accumulator, supporting arithmetic operations, conditional branches, and data transfers. It handles fractions and instructions as data types, with a simple register management system including registers like IR, IBR, MQ, MAR, MDR, and a program counter (PC). &#91;64&#93;

#### John McCarthy, Marvin Minsky, and Artificial Intelligence

The term "artificial intelligence" was coined by [John McCarthy](/John_McCarthy_(computer_scientist)) for a proposal to the [Dartmouth Summer Research Project on Artificial Intelligence](Dartmouth_Summer_Research_Project_on_Artificial_Intelligence), marking the birth of a new field. &#91;66&#93; McCarthy, along with Marvin Minsky, [Nathaniel Rochester](/Nathaniel_Rochester_(computer_scientist)), and [Claude E. Shannon](/Claude_Shannon), initiated this research in 1956.

Their core idea was that if a machine could perform a task, it should be programmable. However, they recognized the human brain's complexity was beyond replication at the time. They explored how machines process information at a hardware level, translating human language into [binary](/Binary_number). &#91;67&#93;

Minsky investigated [artificial neural networks](/Artificial_neural_network), drawing parallels to the human brain, though his results were only partial. &#91;68&#93; McCarthy and Shannon proposed using [mathematical theory](/A_Mathematical_Theory_of_Communication) and [computations](/Computational_complexity_theory) to measure machine efficiency, but again, results were limited. &#91;68&#93;

The concept of [self-modifying code](/Self-modifying_code) was explored as a path to machine self-improvement and increased intelligence. &#91;69&#93; They also considered [computational creativity](/Computational_creativity), wondering if machines could exhibit human-like thinking and fill in missing information. &#91;71&#93;

